gn=\"left\"| [[Battle of Knja\u017eevac]]\n|align=\"right\"| 4\u20137 July 1913\n| [[Vasil Kutinchev]]\n| Vukoman Ara\u010di\u0107\n| Bulgarian victory\n|- style=\"background:#adff2f;\"\n|- style=\"background:#9a56f8;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Battle of Pirot (1913)|Battle of Pirot]]\n|align=\"right\"| 6\u20138 July 1913\n|[[Mihail Savov]]\n| [[Bo\u017eidar Jankovi\u0107]]\n| Serbian victory\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#9a56f8;\"\n|align=\"left\"| Battle of Belogradchik\n|align=\"right\"| 8 July 1913\n|[[Mihail Savov]]\n|[[Bo\u017eidar Jankovi\u0107]]\n| Serbian victory\n|- style=\"background:#adff2f;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Siege of Vidin (1913)|Siege of Vidin]]\n|align=\"right\"| 12\u201318 July 1913\n| Krastyu Marinov\n| Vukoman Ara\u010di\u0107\n| Peace treaty\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#adff2f;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Battle of Kalimanci]]\n|align=\"right\"| 18\u201319 July 1913\n| [[Mihail Savov]]\n| [[Bo\u017eidar Jankovi\u0107]]\n| Bulgarian victory\n|}\n\n====Bulgarian\u2013Ottoman battles====\n{| style=\"width:76%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Battle\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Bulgaria|size=22px}} Commander\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| {{flag|Ottoman Empire|size=22px}} Commander\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Result\n|- style=\"background:#f62f3d;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Second Balkan War#Ottoman Intervention|Second Battle of Adrianople]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1913 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Mihail Savov]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Enver Pasha]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| First Armistice\n|- style=\"background:#adff2f;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Second Balkan War#Treaty of Constantinople|Ottoman Advance of Thrace]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1913 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Vulko Velchev|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ahmed Izzet Pasha|Ahmed Pasha]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Treaty of Constantinople (1913)|Final Armistice]]\n|}\n\n====Bulgarian\u2013Romanian battles====\n{| style=\"width:76%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Battle\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Bulgaria|size=22px}} Commander\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Romania|size=22px}} Commander\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Result\n|- style=\"background:yellow;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Treaty of Bucharest (1913)|Romanian Occupation of Dobruja]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1913 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria|Ferdinand I]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Carol I of Romania]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| First Armistice\n|- style=\"background:#adff2f;\"\n|align=\"left\"| [[Treaty of Bucharest (1913)|Romanian South Western Advance]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1913 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria|Ferdinand I]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Carol I of Romania]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Treaty of Bucharest (1913)|Final Armistice]]\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\nCitizens of Turkey regard the Balkan Wars as a major disaster (''Balkan harbi facias\u0131'') in the [[Ottoman Empire#Defeat and dissolution (1908\u20131922)|nation's history]]. The unexpected fall and sudden relinquishing of Turkish-dominated European territories created a [[Psychological trauma|psycho-traumatic]] event amongst many Turks that triggered the ultimate [[Partitioning of the Ottoman Empire|collapse]] of the empire itself within five years. [[Naz\u0131m Pasha]], Chief of Staff of the [[Ottoman Army]], was held responsible for the failure and was assassinated on 23 January 1913 during the [[1913 Ottoman coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref>Gul Tokay. \"Ottoman diplomacy, the Balkan Wars and the Great Powers\". In Dominik Geppert, William Mulligan, Andreas Rose, eds. ''The Wars before the Great War'' {{ISBN|978-1-107-06347-1}}, 2015, p. 70</ref>\n\nMost Greeks regard the Balkan Wars as a period of epic achievements. They managed to liberate and gain by conquest territories that were inhabited by Greeks since the ancient times and were doouble the size of that time Greek Kingdom. The Greek Army, very little in numbers and ill-equipped in comparison to the superior Ottoman but also Bulgarian and Serbian armies, won very important battles that made it accountable to the Great Powers' chessplay. Two great personalities rose in the Greek political arena, Prime Minister [[Eleftherios Venizelos]], the leading mind behind the Greek foreign policy, and Crown Prince, and later King, [[Konstantinos I]], the major General of the greek Army.<ref>{{cite book |title=\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2(History of the Hellenic Nation) |date=1974 |publisher=Ekdotiki Athinon |location=Athens, Greece |isbn=9789602131107 |edition=Vol. 14}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Mavrogordatos |first1=Georgios |title=1915, \u039f \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03c7\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 (1915, The National Division) |date=2015 |publisher=Ekdoseis Patakis |location=Athens |isbn=9789601664989 |pages=33-35 |edition=VIII}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[International relations (1814\u20131919)]]\n\nSince the area has been referred to as the [[Balkans]], notable conflicts have included the following:\n\n*The [[Ottoman wars in Europe]]\n*The [[Serbo-Bulgarian War]] (1885)\n*The [[Albanian Revolt of 1910]]\n*The [[Albanian Revolt of 1911]]\n*The [[Albanian Revolt of 1912]]\n*The [[Balkans Campaign (World War I)]]\n*The [[Balkans Campaign (World War II)]]\n*The [[Yugoslav Wars]] (1991\u20131999)\n*[[Destruction of the Thracian Bulgarians in 1913]]\n*[[List of places burned during the Balkan Wars]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Batakovi\u0107|editor-first=Du\u0161an T.|editor-link=Du\u0161an T. Batakovi\u0107|title=Histoire du peuple serbe|trans-title=History of the Serbian People|language=French|date=2005|location=Lausanne|publisher=L\u2019Age d\u2019Homme|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0jA_LdH6nsC}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Boeckh|first1=Katrin|last2=Rutar|first2=Sabina|title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0IhaDQEACAAJ|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-44641-7}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=\u0106irkovi\u0107|first=Sima|authorlink=Sima \u0106irkovi\u0107|title=The Serbs|year=2004|location=Malden|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Wc-DWRzoeIC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Clark|first=Christopher|title=The Sleepwalkers: How Europe Went to War in 1914|chapter=Balkan Entanglements|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780061146657|url-access=registration|year=2013|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-219922-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Crampton|first=R. J.|title=The hollow detente: Anglo-German relations in the Balkans, 1911\u20131914|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pRhFAQAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=G. Prior|isbn=978-0-391-02159-4}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Erickson|first1=Edward J.|last2=Bush|first2=Brighton C.|title=Defeat in Detail: The Ottoman Army in the Balkans, 1912\u20131913  |year=2003|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0-275-97888-5|ref=harv}}\n* Ginio, Eyal.  ''The Ottoman Culture of Defeat: The Balkan Wars and their Aftermath'' (Oxford UP, 2016) 377 pp. [http://www.h-net.msu.edu/reviews/showrev.php?id=52198 online review]\n* {{cite book|last=Hall|first=Richard C.|title=The Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913: Prelude to the First World War|edition=1st|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-22946-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Helmreich|first=Ernst Christian|title=The Diplomacy of the Balkan Wars, 1912\u20131913|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvVMMQAACAAJ|year=1938|publisher=Harvard University Press|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Jelavich|first=Barbara|au