{"title_page": "La Cure", "text_new": "{{Infobox Swiss town\n | subject_name\t\t= La Cure\n | municipality_name\t= La Cure\n | municipality_type\t= municipality\n | image_photo          = La-Cure-Douane.jpg\n | image_caption        = Hotel Arbez in La Cure.  The border runs lengthwise through the two buildings, passing just to the left of the [[mural]].  The mural and everything to the right of it lies in Switzerland; France lies to the left.\n | imagepath_coa\t= \n | map\t\t\t=\n | languages\t\t= French\n | canton\t\t= Vaud\n | iso-code-region \t= CH-VD\n | district\t\t= [[Nyon (district)|Nyon]]\n |coordinates  = {{coord|46|28|N|6|04|E|display=inline,title}}\n |lat_NS=N|long_EW=E\n | postal_code\t\t= 1265\n | municipality_code\t= \n<!-- | area\t\t= ...Used if the municipality_code is incorrect... Area in km2. -->\n | elevation\t\t= 1028\n | population\t\t= \n | website\t\t= \n | mayor\t\t= \n |mayor_asof=|mayor_party=\n | mayor_title\t=\n |list_of_mayors\t=\n | places\t\t=\n | demonym\t\t=\n | neighboring_municipalities= \n | twintowns\t\t=\n|}}\n\n'''La Cure''' is a small village located {{convert|30|mi|km|sigfig=1|order=flip}} north of [[Geneva, Switzerland|Geneva]], Switzerland.  Part of the village lies in Switzerland, and part in France, with the boundary dividing not only the village itself, but at least four structures within it.  One of these structures is the [[Hotel Arbez]], in which the dining hall and other rooms are bisected by the border.\n\n==History==\nUntil 1862, La Cure was entirely in France.  France and Switzerland had previously disputed possession of the strategically important Vall\u00e9e des Dappes, which was controlled by the latter until in 1862, the Swiss accepted an offer to exchange that territory for another piece just to the north and east; the new boundary was drawn directly through La Cure.  According to the [[Treaty of Dappes]], which formalized the swap, any buildings existing at the time that the new line was demarcated were not to be disturbed, even if the boundary bisected them.<ref>[http://geosite.jankrogh.com/borders/chfr/La_Cure/index.html La Cure Photos and Maps]</ref>\n\nToday, the border passes through the Hotel Arbez (see below); in addition, it bisects at least two residences, and a [[pub]].<ref>[http://geosite.jankrogh.com/borders/chfr/La_Cure/index.html La Cure Photos and Maps]</ref>\n\n==Railway==\nThere is a Swiss Railways narrow gauge railway line, the [[Nyon\u2013St-Cergue\u2013Morez Railway]], that runs from Nyon to La Cure.\n\n==Hotel Arbez==\nTaking advantage of the delay between negotiation of the treaty and its final ratification by the [[Swiss Parliament]], a local businessman named Ponthus constructed a new structure in 1863 on the new borderline.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref>  Originally Ponthus operated a [[grocery store]] in the Swiss section of the building, with a bar in the French section, hoping to turn the cross-border business to his advantage.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref> In 1921, Jules-Jean Arbez purchased the building, and turned it into a hotel.\n\n[[File:Plaque fronti\u00e8re - La Cure.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Border plaque on a building in La Cure]]\n[[File:La-Cure-1.JPG|thumb|280px|La Cure, aerial view.]]\nToday, the Franco-Swiss border passes through the kitchen, dining room, hallway and several rooms of the hotel.  In two rooms (including the [[suite (hotel)|honeymoon suite]]) the beds themselves are bisected by the boundary, while in another, the bathroom is in France, while the rest of the room is in Switzerland.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref><ref>[http://www.myswitzerland.com/en-us/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse.html My Switzerland: Hotel Arbez]</ref>\n\nDuring the [[German occupation of France during World War II|German occupation of France]] in [[World War II]], their troops were allowed to enter the French side of the hotel, but were strictly prohibited from crossing to the Swiss side.  Since the stairway to the upper floor started in French territory but ended in Switzerland, the Germans were not permitted to access any of the upper rooms, which became a refuge for refugees and [[French Resistance]] members.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref>  The hotel was chosen in 1962 for negotiation of the [[\u00c9vian Accords]] between France and [[Algeria]], which resulted in the independence of the latter.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Haskell Free Library and Opera House]], a library located half in [[Derby Line, Vermont]], United States and half in [[Stanstead, Quebec]], Canada.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Commons category|La Cure}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.arbezie-hotel.com/ Hotel Arbez].  Website for the hotel; primarily in French, with limited English translation.\n*[http://geosite.jankrogh.com/borders/chfr/La_Cure/index.html La Cure: Photos and Maps].  Offers several large photos of the village and its buildings (with lines showing the border's location), as well as maps of the area.\n*[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez: Half in France and Half in Switzerland].  Offers photos of the interior and exterior of the Hotel Arbez, with lines showing the precise location of the border in each.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Vaud]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Switzerland border]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Switzerland border crossings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Swiss town\n | subject_name\t\t= La Cure\n | municipality_name\t= La Cure\n | municipality_type\t= municipality\n | image_photo          = La-Cure-Douane.jpg\n | image_caption        = Hotel Arbez in La Cure.  The border runs lengthwise through the two buildings, passing just to the left of the [[mural]].  The mural and everything to the right of it lies in Switzerland; France lies to the left.\n | imagepath_coa\t= \n | map\t\t\t=\n | languages\t\t= French\n | canton\t\t= Vaud\n | iso-code-region \t= CH-VD\n | district\t\t= [[Nyon (district)|Nyon]]\n |coordinates  = {{coord|46|28|N|6|04|E|display=inline,title}}\n |lat_NS=N|long_EW=E\n | postal_code\t\t= 1265\n | municipality_code\t= \n<!-- | area\t\t= ...Used if the municipality_code is incorrect... Area in km2. -->\n | elevation\t\t= 1028\n | population\t\t= \n | website\t\t= \n | mayor\t\t= \n |mayor_asof=|mayor_party=\n | mayor_title\t=\n |list_of_mayors\t=\n | places\t\t=\n | demonym\t\t=\n | neighboring_municipalities= \n | twintowns\t\t=\n|}}\n\n'''La Cure''' is a small village located thirty miles north of [[Geneva, Switzerland|Geneva]], Switzerland.  Part of the village lies in Switzerland, and part in France, with the boundary dividing not only the village itself, but at least four structures within it.  One of these structures is the [[Hotel Arbez]], in which the dining hall and other rooms are bisected by the border.\n\n==History==\nUntil 1862, La Cure was entirely in France.  France and Switzerland had previously disputed possession of the strategically important Vall\u00e9e des Dappes, which was controlled by the latter until in 1862, the Swiss accepted an offer to exchange that territory for another piece just to the north and east; the new boundary was drawn directly through La Cure.  According to the [[Treaty of Dappes]], which formalized the swap, any buildings existing at the time that the new line was demarcated were not to be disturbed, even if the boundary bisected them.<ref>[http://geosite.jankrogh.com/borders/chfr/La_Cure/index.html La Cure Photos and Maps]</ref>\n\nToday, the border passes through the Hotel Arbez (see below); in addition, it bisects at least two residences, and a [[pub]].<ref>[http://geosite.jankrogh.com/borders/chfr/La_Cure/index.html La Cure Photos and Maps]</ref>\n\n==Railway==\nThere is a Swiss Railways narrow gauge railway line, the [[Nyon\u2013St-Cergue\u2013Morez Railway]], that runs from Nyon to La Cure.\n\n==Hotel Arbez==\nTaking advantage of the delay between negotiation of the treaty and its final ratification by the [[Swiss Parliament]], a local businessman named Ponthus constructed a new structure in 1863 on the new borderline.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref>  Originally Ponthus operated a [[grocery store]] in the Swiss section of the building, with a bar in the French section, hoping to turn the cross-border business to his advantage.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref> In 1921, Jules-Jean Arbez purchased the building, and turned it into a hotel.\n\n[[File:Plaque fronti\u00e8re - La Cure.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Border plaque on a building in La Cure]]\n[[File:La-Cure-1.JPG|thumb|280px|La Cure, aerial view.]]\nToday, the Franco-Swiss border passes through the kitchen, dining room, hallway and several rooms of the hotel.  In two rooms (including the [[suite (hotel)|honeymoon suite]]) the beds themselves are bisected by the boundary, while in another, the bathroom is in France, while the rest of the room is in Switzerland.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref><ref>[http://www.myswitzerland.com/en-us/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse.html My Switzerland: Hotel Arbez]</ref>\n\nDuring the [[German occupation of France during World War II|German occupation of France]] in [[World War II]], their troops were allowed to enter the French side of the hotel, but were strictly prohibited from crossing to the Swiss side.  Since the stairway to the upper floor started in French territory but ended in Switzerland, the Germans were not permitted to access any of the upper rooms, which became a refuge for refugees and [[French Resistance]] members.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref>  The hotel was chosen in 1962 for negotiation of the [[\u00c9vian Accords]] between France and [[Algeria]], which resulted in the independence of the latter.<ref>[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Haskell Free Library and Opera House]], a library located half in [[Derby Line, Vermont]], United States and half in [[Stanstead, Quebec]], Canada.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Commons category|La Cure}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.arbezie-hotel.com/ Hotel Arbez].  Website for the hotel; primarily in French, with limited English translation.\n*[http://geosite.jankrogh.com/borders/chfr/La_Cure/index.html La Cure: Photos and Maps].  Offers several large photos of the village and its buildings (with lines showing the border's location), as well as maps of the area.\n*[http://www.amusingplanet.com/2012/03/hotel-arbez-franco-suisse-located-half.html Hotel Arbez: Half in France and Half in Switzerland].  Offers photos of the interior and exterior of the Hotel Arbez, with lines showing the precise location of the border in each.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Vaud]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Switzerland border]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Switzerland border crossings]]\n", "name_user": "Archon 2488", "label": "safe", "comment": "add convert template; style per MOSNUM", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Cure"}
{"title_page": "Wages for housework", "text_new": "The '''International Wages for Housework Campaign''' was a feminist global social movement, which grew out of the International Feminist Collective in [[Italy]] in 1972 and organized resistance and public debate on the social formations produced by gendered labor and [[reproductive labor]], for example domestic work such as [[Homemaking|housework]], [[childcare]], [[gender discrimination]], and the socially reinforced performance of [[gender roles]], gendered desire, and leisure inequality. The Campaign's platform included the women's right to work outside of the home, [[Unemployment benefits in Italy|unemployment benefits]], parental leave, and equal pay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.generation-online.org/p/fpdallacosta1.htm|title=The door to the garden|last=www.generation-online.org|first=Mariarosa Dalla Costa + EE + AB|website=www.generation-online.org|access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nplusonemag.com\" /> The Campaign was formed in [[Padua]], Italy by [[Selma James]], [[Brigitte Galtier]], [[Mariarosa Dalla Costa]], and [[Silvia Federici]]. A major tenet of the campaign was that reproductive labor is the foundation of industrial work, in its important role in the maintenance and care of gendered male workers, yet a type of labor not recognized as productive enough to be [[wage labor]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=James|first=Selma|title=Is Transformation Possible? They Say We Can't. We Must|jstor=20838923|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=38|issue=1|page=42|year=2008}}</ref> \n\nThe demands for the Wages for Housework used [[Marxist]] frameworks to think through the reliance of capitalist economies on exploitative labor practices against certain populations.<ref name=\"nplusonemag.com\">[http://nplusonemag.com/more-smiles-more-money \"More Smiles, More Money\"], ''N+1 Magazine'', August 2013.</ref> [[Mariarosa Dalla Costa]] and some participants in the Wages for Housework campaign were enmeshed in the intellectual movement ''[[operaismo]],'' which developed around factory strikes in [[Northern Italy]] in the 1970s. The Wages for Housework Campaign shared with ''operaismo'' the idea that fair working conditions including wages are key to the social recognition of labor. ''Operaismo'' encouraged workers to act in their direct interests, and engage in factory strikes to demand better conditions. The Wages for Housework campaign applied also shared discussions about the [[social factory]] with [[operaismo]]; whereby \"the whole of society lives as a function of the factory and the factory extends its exclusive domination to the whole of society\".<ref name=\"F&S\">{{cite web|last1=Tronti|first1=Mario|title=Factory and Society|url=https://operaismoinenglish.wordpress.com/2013/06/13/factory-and-society/|website=Operaismo in English|accessdate=6 May 2017|date=1962}}</ref> The campaign activities included student protests, community workshops, and direct action protest. \n\nWages for Housework published a [[autonomist Marxism|Marxist autonomist]] journal, ''Mat\u00e9riaux pour l\u2019intervention''. Several publications grew out of its ideas, which expanded on the claims of the original group and of more general topics in labor and exploitation. In Italy, ''Quaderni rossi'', published by [[Raniero Panzieri]] and [[Mario Tronti]], dealt with a variety of topics relating to the class struggle.\n\n==United States==\nIn 1973, [[Silvia Federici]] helped start Wages for Housework groups in the US and in 1975, the Wages for Housework opened an office in [[Brooklyn]], New York at 288 B. 8th St. The New York group was called the \"Wages for Housework Committee.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.metamute.org/editorial/articles/permanent-reproductive-crisis-interview-silvia-federici|title = Permanent Reproductive Crisis: An Interview with Silvia Federici|date = March 2013|accessdate = |website = Meta Mute|publisher = |last = Vishmidt|first = Marina}}</ref> [http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/sexualhealth/WagesForHousework.pdf Flyers] handed out in support of the New York Wages for Housework Committee [http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce/Wages_for_Housework.pdf called for all women] to join regardless of marital status, nationality, sexual orientation, number of children, or employment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce/Wages_for_Housework.pdf|title = The Campaign for Wages for Housework|date = 1975|accessdate = 22 October 2015|website = bcrw.barnard.edu|publisher = Barnard Center for Research on Women|last = |first = }}</ref> In 1975 Federici published ''Wages Against Housework,'' the book most commonly associated with the movement.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBranches of the Wages for Housework Committee appeared in other cities across America. They were organized in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[San Francisco]], [[Chicago]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Tulsa]], and [[Cleveland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Poor Workers' Union: Rebuilding Labor from Below|last = Tait|first = Vanessa|publisher = South End Press|year = 2005|isbn = 978-0896087149|location = Boston|pages = [https://archive.org/details/poorworkersunion00tait/page/38 38]|url = https://archive.org/details/poorworkersunion00tait/page/38}}</ref> Along with these committees, other autonomous organizations that fall within the Wages for Housework campaign began to organize within the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://freedomarchives.org/Documents/Finder/DOC500_scans/500.020.Wages.for.Housework.pdf|title = The International Wages for Housework Campaign|date = |accessdate = 10 October 2015|website = Freedomarchives.org|publisher = The Freedom Archives|last = |first = }}</ref> For example, in 1974 International Black Women for Wages for Housework was founded by [[Margaret Prescod]] and Wilmette Brown in New York City. Prescod also founded the Black Women for Wages for Housework in Los Angeles alongside Sidney Ross-Risden in 1980. The Black Women for Wages for Housework focused on not only unpaid housework for the average housewife, but specific issues of black and third world women. They called for reparations for \"slavery, imperialism and neo-colonialism.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/1987-05-07/news/vw-4294_1_unremunerated-work|title = Waging the War Over Wages: Fight for Homemaker Pay has Seen Ups, Downs|date = May 1987|accessdate = 6 November 2015|website = Los Angeles Times|last = Hendrix|first = Kathleen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Feminists Who Changed America, 1963\u20131975|last = Love|first = Barbara|publisher = University of Illinois Press|year = 2006|isbn = 978-0252031892|location = Chicago|pages = [https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love/page/368 368]|url = https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love/page/368}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url = http://articles.latimes.com/1985-07-28/news/vw-5698_1_unpaid-work|title = Campaign Catches On: L.A. Pair Seek Wages for Women's Unpaid Work|last = Hendrix|first = Kathleen|date = 28 July  1985|work = Newspaper|access-date = 22 October 2015|via = Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nBoth San Francisco and Philadelphia were home to Wages Due Lesbians, an organization that was first created in Britain in 1975. Wages Due Lesbians called for wages for housework along with extra wages for lesbians for \"the additional physical and emotional housework of surviving in a hostile and prejudiced society, recognized as work and paid for so all women have the economic power to afford sexual choices.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Wages Due Lesbians also worked alongside The Lesbian Mothers' National Defense Fund, founded in 1974 and based in [[Seattle]], which aimed to help lesbian mothers who were a part of custody cases after coming out.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.outhistory.org/exhibits/show/lmndf/lmndf|title = The Lesbian Mothers National Defense Fund, the 1970s through 1990s|date = |accessdate = 6 November 2015|website = outhistory.org|publisher = Out History|last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = The A to Z of the Lesbian Liberation Movement: Still the Rage|last = Myers|first = JoAnne|publisher = Scarecrow Press|year = 2009|isbn = 978-0810863279|location = Plymouth|pages = xxxvi}}</ref>\n\nSan Francisco was also home to the U.S. PROStitutes Collective (US PROS). US PROS was created in 1982 to help decriminalize prostitution and also prevent men, women, and children from being forced into prostitution.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = US PROS Collective|url = http://uspros.net/|website = US PROS Collective|accessdate = 23 October 2015|language = en-US}}</ref> Likewise, Tulsa housed the No Bad Women, Just Bad Laws Coalitions. It was founded by Ruth Taylor Todasco in 1981 and also focused on the decriminalization of sex work.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Feminists Who Changed America, 1963\u20131965|last = Love|first = |publisher = |year = 2006|isbn = |location = |page = 463}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://hivandthelaw.com/sites/default/files/null/Overs_SexworkerRights.pdf|title = 'No Bad Women, Just Bad Laws': Three Decades of Sex Work Law Reform Advocacy|date = 2012|accessdate = 22 October 2015|website = HIV and the Law|publisher = Criminalize Hate Not HIV|last = Overs|first = Cheryl}}</ref>\n\n== Italy ==\nIn 1974, the Wages for Housework Campaign started in Italy. To celebrate, one of the founding members [[Mariarosa Dalla Costa]] gave a speech entitled \"A General Strike\" in [[Mestre]], Italy. In this speech she talks about how no strike before has ever been a general strike before, but instead, only a strike for male workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caringlabor.wordpress.com/2010/10/20/mariarosa-dalla-costa-a-general-strike/|title=A General Strike|last=Dalla Costa|first=Mariarosa|date=21 October 2010}}</ref>  \n\n== Social wage campaigns ==\nWages for Housework is part of more general [[social wage]] campaigns in the 1970s interested in [[late capitalism]].  These campaigns used analysis of [[Fordist]] compromises during the twentieth century to argue that [[family wages]] or social security payments had amounted to wages paid for housework in the advanced capitalist West.<ref name=Himmelweit>{{cite journal|last=Himmelweit|first=Susan F | last2 = Mohun | first2 = Simon | author-link1 = Susan Himmelweit | title = Domestic labour and capital |journal= Cambridge Journal of Economics |date=1977 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages= 15\u201331 |url =http://cje.oxfordjournals.org/content/1/1/15.full.pdf+html |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.cje.a035348 }}</ref><ref>Zo\u00eb Fairbairns, [http://www.newint.org/features/1988/03/05/wages/ \"Wages For Housework\"], ''New Internationalist'', issue 181, March 1988.</ref> A number of other autonomous organizations interested in compensation for domestic labor were formed in 1975: Black Women for Wages for Housework, Wages Due Lesbians, the [[English Collective of Prostitutes]] (ECP) and some years later WinVisible (women with visible and invisible disabilities).\n\n==Early influences==\nA number of early feminists focused women's economic independence along with the role of housewife in relation to women's oppression. In 1898 [[Charlotte Perkins Gilman]] published ''[[Women and Economics]].'' This book argued for paid housework 74 years before the International Wages for Housework Campaign was founded as well as arguing to expand the definition of women in the home.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Women and Economics: A Study of the Economic Relation Between Men and Women as a Factor in Social Evolution|last=Perkins Gilman|first=Charlotte|publisher=Small, Maynard & Company|year=1898|isbn=|location=United States|pages=}}</ref> She asserts that \"wives, as earners through domestic service, are entitled to the wages of cooks, housemaids, nursemaids, seamstresses, or housekeepers\" and that providing women economic independence is key to their liberation. [[Alva Myrdal]], a Swedish feminist, focused on state sponsored child care and housing, in order to ease the burden of parenting off mothers.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The Essential Feminist Reader|last=Freedman|first=Estelle|publisher=Modern Library|year=2007|isbn=9780812974607|location=|pages=}}</ref> In [[Simone de Beauvoir]]'s ''[[The Second Sex]],'' in which de Beauvoir asserts that women cannot find transcendence through unpaid house work.<ref name=\":4\" /> This idea is echoed in ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]'' by [[Betty Friedan]] when she discusses how women are unable to feel fulfilled in the home. ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]'' defined many second wave feminist goals, and the connection between the Wages for Housework Campaign and this work cannot be overlooked.<ref name=\":4\" />    \n\nIn 1965 Alison Ravetz published \"Modern Technology and an Ancient Occupation: Housework in Present-Day Society\"<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Modern Technology and an Ancient Occupation: Housework in Present-Day Society|journal = Technology and Culture|volume = 6|issue = 2|pages = 256\u2013260|last=Ravetz|first=Alison|jstor = 3101078|year = 1965|doi = 10.2307/3101078}}</ref> which critiques housework being a womanly duty post industrial revolution. The idea here is that since housework has become less labor intensive since then, it is even less fulfilling than ever before. This echos a similar argument made by [[Alva Myrdal]].\n\n==Recent history==\nThe demands of the Wages for Housework Campaign have been applied to many more recent debates in the gendered aspects of labor including, reproductive rights, sex work, and demands for women in leadership roles in business.<ref name=\"nplusonemag.com\" />\n\nSilvia Federici and several others from the early campaign have continued to publish books and articles related to the demands of Wages for Housework including: ''Revolution at Point Zero: Housework, Reproduction, and Feminist Struggle'' (2012), ''Wages for Housework: The New York Committee 1972\u20131977, History, Theory, and Documents'' (2017).\n\nThe Wages for Housework Campaign called for a [[Global Women's Strike|Global Women\u2019s Strike]] (GWS) on March 8, 2000, demanding among other things, \u201cPayment for all caring work \u2013 in wages, pensions, land and other resources.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=James|first=Selma|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/08/iceland-global-womens-strike-protest|title=Decades after Iceland\u2019s \u2018day off\u2019, our women\u2019s strike is stronger than ever {{!}} Selma James|date=2018-03-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Women from over 60 countries around the world participated in the protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/mar/07/gender|title=Stop the world and change it: the global women's strike|last=Staff|first=Guardian|date=2000-03-07|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since 2000 the GWS network has continued the call for a living wage for women and other caregivers, and they have led or joined campaigns focused on pay equity, violence against women, and the rights of sex workers, among other issues.\n\nIn 2019 the Global Women\u2019s Strike (GWS) network and Wages for Housework Campaign joined a coalition of organizations calling for a Green New Deal for Europe (GNDE).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gndforeurope.com/|title=Green New Deal for Europe|website=Green New Deal for Europe|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Wages for Housework Campaign co-founder, [[Selma James]] (with other GWS members), contributed to the GNDE platform report which includes a policy recommendation to \"fund a care income to compensate unpaid activities like care for people, the urban environment, and the natural world.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://report.gndforeurope.com/|title=A Blueprint for Europe's Just Transition|website=Green New Deal for Europe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The idea of a \u201ccare income\u201d expands the original demand for wages for housework to include all indispensable yet unpaid (or underpaid) work that involves caring for people and the planet, or caring for life. \n\nOn April 9, 2020, in response to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19 coronavirus]] pandemic and the climate emergency, the Global Women\u2019s Strike and Women of Colour GWS networks released an open letter to governments amplifying their call for a \u201ccare income.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalwomenstrike.net/press-statement-in-response-to-covid-19-and-the-climate-emergency-organizations-around-the-world-call-for-a-care-income-now/|title=PRESS STATEMENT: In response to Covid-19 and the climate emergency: organizations around the world call for a Care Income Now! \u2013 GLOBAL WOMEN'S STRIKE / WAGES FOR HOUSEWORK / SELMA JAMES|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nCritics have argued that providing wages for housework could further reinforce or institutionalize specific gendered roles vis-\u00e0-vis housework, and care work more broadly. Rather than providing wages for housework, they argue, the goal should be liberation from it and the demeaning and subordinating role of 'housewife'. Instead feminists should focus on increasing women\u2019s opportunities in the paid workforce with pay equity, while promoting a more equal distribution of unpaid work in the household. Proponents of Wages for Housework also support equal opportunity and pay equity, however, they argue that entering the workforce does nothing to directly challenge the social role of women or result in a more equitable distribution of unpaid care work in the household. In fact, more often than not, women who have entered the paid workforce often face a \u201cdouble shift\u201d of work, the first paid work in the labor market and the second unpaid housework.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Federici, Silvia, author.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1129596584|title=Revolution at point zero : housework, reproduction, and feminist struggle|isbn=978-1-77113-494-1|oclc=1129596584}}</ref> According to one global estimate, women spend 4.5 hours of unpaid work per day, twice as many hours as men do on average.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gupta|first=Alisha Haridasani|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/23/us/unpaid-work-economy-davos.html|title=Women, Burdened With Unpaid Labor, Bear Brunt of Global Inequality|date=2020-01-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOther criticisms include the concern that providing wages for housework would commodify intimate human relationships of love and care and would subsume them into capitalist relations. However, proponents of wages for housework contest this \u201creductive view\u201d of their proposal. For instance, according to [[Silvia Federici]] the demand for wages for housework is not just about remuneration for unpaid work or women\u2019s financial empowerment and independence. Rather, it is a political perspective and a revolutionary strategy to make invisible work more visible, to demystify and disrupt the structural reliance of capitalism on the unpaid work of (mostly) women, and to subvert the supposed natural social role of \u201chousewife\u201d that capital has invented for women.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Federici, Silvia, author.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1129596584|title=Revolution at point zero : housework, reproduction, and feminist struggle|isbn=978-1-77113-494-1|oclc=1129596584}}</ref>\n\nWhat\u2019s more, the payment of wages for housework would mean that capital would have to pay for the immense amount of unpaid care work (undertaken largely by women) that currently reproduces the labor force. According to a report by Oxfam and the Institute for Women\u2019s Policy Research, the monetary value of unpaid care work is estimated at nearly $11 trillion a year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wezerek|first=Gus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/04/opinion/women-unpaid-labor.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Women\u2019s Unpaid Labor is Worth $10,900,000,000,000|date=2020-03-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|last2=Ghodsee|first2=Kristen R.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfamamerica.org/explore/research-publications/time-care/|title=Time to Care|website=www.oxfamamerica.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> This amounts to an enormous subsidy to the capitalist economy, and paying for it would likely render the current system uneconomic, subverting the social relations in the process. \n\nMonetary estimates of this kind are used to demonstrate the scale of unpaid work in relation to more visible waged work. However, proponents of wages for housework do not advocate for the marketization and commodification of unpaid care work. Instead they have promoted public funding for these schemes as part of a larger project of recognizing and revaluing the indispensable role of unpaid care work for society and the economy. Some feminist scholars have also called for the creation of new commons-based systems of care and basic provisioning that operate outside of the market and state, and for the defense of existing commons, especially in communities of the [[Global South]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wealthofthecommons.org/essay/feminism-and-politics-commons|title=Feminism and the Politics of the Commons {{!}} The Wealth of the Commons|website=wealthofthecommons.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* [[Louise Toupin]]. ''Le salaire au travail m\u00e9nager. Chronique d'une lutte f\u00e9ministe internationale (1972\u20131977)'' \u00c9ditions du Remue-M\u00e9nage, 2014.\n* Silvia Federici. ''Revolution at Point Zero: Housework, Reproduction, and Feminist Struggle.'' PM Press, 2012. \n*  Silvia Federici. ''[https://monoskop.org/images/2/23/Federici_Silvia_Wages_Against_Housework_1975.pdf Wages Against Housework]''. Published jointly by the Power of Women Collective and Falling Wall Press, 1975. Link goes to full text of the book.\n* Cox, Nicole, and Silvia Federici. ''[http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce.htm Counter-planning from the kitchen: wages for housework : a perspective on capital and the Left.''] New York: New York Wages for Housework Committee. 1976.\n* Dalla Costa, Mariarosa, and Selma James. ''The Power of Women and the Subversion of the Community.'' Bristol: Falling Wall Press Ltd. 1975.\n* James, Selma, Nina Lopez, and Marcus Rediker. 2012. ''Sex, Race and Class \u2013 The Perspective of Winning a Selection of Writings 1952\u20132011.'' Chicago: PM Press. http://public.eblib.com/EBLPublic/PublicView.do?ptiID=867353.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Microwork]]\n* [[Post-Fordism]]\n* [[Knowledge economy]]\n* [[Knowledge market]]\n*[[Marxist feminism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nbjournal.org/2007/07/selma-james-and-the-wages-for-housework-campaign/ Selma James and the Wages for Housework Campaign - article by Shemon Salam in New Beginnings, a journal of independent labour]\n* [http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce.htm \"Women in the Workforce\" collections. Barnard Archive.]\n* [http://globalwomenstrike.net/ Global Women's Strike/ Wages For Housework/ Selma James website]\n*[https://www.gndforeurope.com/campaign Green New Deal for Europe campaign website] \n\n[[Category:Feminism]]\n[[Category:Wages and salaries]]\n[[Category:Trade unions]]\n[[Category:Autonomism]]\n", "text_old": "The '''International Wages for Housework Campaign''' was a feminist global social movement, which grew out of the International Feminist Collective in [[Italy]] in 1972 and organized resistance and public debate on the social formations produced by gendered labor and [[reproductive labor]], for example domestic work such as [[Homemaking|housework]], [[childcare]], [[gender discrimination]], and the socially reinforced performance of [[gender roles]], gendered desire, and leisure inequality. The Campaign's platform included the women's right to work outside of the home, [[Unemployment benefits in Italy|unemployment benefits]], parental leave, and equal pay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.generation-online.org/p/fpdallacosta1.htm|title=The door to the garden|last=www.generation-online.org|first=Mariarosa Dalla Costa + EE + AB|website=www.generation-online.org|access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nplusonemag.com\" /> The Campaign was formed in [[Padua]], Italy by [[Selma James]], [[Brigitte Galtier]], [[Mariarosa Dalla Costa]], and [[Silvia Federici]]. A major tenet of the campaign was that reproductive labor is the foundation of industrial work, in its important role in the maintenance and care of gendered male workers, yet a type of labor not recognized as productive enough to be [[wage labor]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=James|first=Selma|title=Is Transformation Possible? They Say We Can't. We Must|jstor=20838923|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=38|issue=1|page=42|year=2008}}</ref> \n\nThe demands for the Wages for Housework used [[Marxist]] frameworks to think through the reliance of capitalist economies on exploitative labor practices against certain populations.<ref name=\"nplusonemag.com\">[http://nplusonemag.com/more-smiles-more-money \"More Smiles, More Money\"], ''N+1 Magazine'', August 2013.</ref> [[Mariarosa Dalla Costa]] and some participants in the Wages for Housework campaign were enmeshed in the intellectual movement ''[[operaismo]],'' which developed around factory strikes in [[Northern Italy]] in the 1970s. The Wages for Housework Campaign shared with ''operaismo'' the idea that fair working conditions including wages are key to the social recognition of labor. ''Operaismo'' encouraged workers to act in their direct interests, and engage in factory strikes to demand better conditions. The Wages for Housework campaign applied also shared discussions about the [[social factory]] with [[operaismo]]; whereby \"the whole of society lives as a function of the factory and the factory extends its exclusive domination to the whole of society\".<ref name=\"F&S\">{{cite web|last1=Tronti|first1=Mario|title=Factory and Society|url=https://operaismoinenglish.wordpress.com/2013/06/13/factory-and-society/|website=Operaismo in English|accessdate=6 May 2017|date=1962}}</ref> The campaign activities included student protests, community workshops, and direct action protest. \n\nWages for Housework published a [[autonomist Marxism|Marxist autonomist]] journal, ''Mat\u00e9riaux pour l\u2019intervention''. Several publications grew out of its ideas, which expanded on the claims of the original group and of more general topics in labor and exploitation. In Italy, ''Quaderni rossi'', published by [[Raniero Panzieri]] and [[Mario Tronti]], dealt with a variety of topics relating to the class struggle.\n\n==United States==\nIn 1973, [[Silvia Federici]] helped start Wages for Housework groups in the US and in 1975, the Wages for Housework opened an office in [[Brooklyn]], New York at 288 B. 8th St. The New York group was called the \"Wages for Housework Committee.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.metamute.org/editorial/articles/permanent-reproductive-crisis-interview-silvia-federici|title = Permanent Reproductive Crisis: An Interview with Silvia Federici|date = March 2013|accessdate = |website = Meta Mute|publisher = |last = Vishmidt|first = Marina}}</ref> [http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/sexualhealth/WagesForHousework.pdf Flyers] handed out in support of the New York Wages for Housework Committee [http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce/Wages_for_Housework.pdf called for all women] to join regardless of marital status, nationality, sexual orientation, number of children, or employment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce/Wages_for_Housework.pdf|title = The Campaign for Wages for Housework|date = 1975|accessdate = 22 October 2015|website = bcrw.barnard.edu|publisher = Barnard Center for Research on Women|last = |first = }}</ref> In 1975 Federici published ''Wages Against Housework,'' the book most commonly associated with the movement.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nBranches of the Wages for Housework Committee appeared in other cities across America. They were organized in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[San Francisco]], [[Chicago]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Tulsa]], and [[Cleveland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Poor Workers' Union: Rebuilding Labor from Below|last = Tait|first = Vanessa|publisher = South End Press|year = 2005|isbn = 978-0896087149|location = Boston|pages = [https://archive.org/details/poorworkersunion00tait/page/38 38]|url = https://archive.org/details/poorworkersunion00tait/page/38}}</ref> Along with these committees, other autonomous organizations that fall within the Wages for Housework campaign began to organize within the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://freedomarchives.org/Documents/Finder/DOC500_scans/500.020.Wages.for.Housework.pdf|title = The International Wages for Housework Campaign|date = |accessdate = 10 October 2015|website = Freedomarchives.org|publisher = The Freedom Archives|last = |first = }}</ref> For example, in 1974 International Black Women for Wages for Housework was founded by [[Margaret Prescod]] and Wilmette Brown in New York City. Prescod also founded the Black Women for Wages for Housework in Los Angeles alongside Sidney Ross-Risden in 1980. The Black Women for Wages for Housework focused on not only unpaid housework for the average housewife, but specific issues of black and third world women. They called for reparations for \"slavery, imperialism and neo-colonialism.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/1987-05-07/news/vw-4294_1_unremunerated-work|title = Waging the War Over Wages: Fight for Homemaker Pay has Seen Ups, Downs|date = May 1987|accessdate = 6 November 2015|website = Los Angeles Times|last = Hendrix|first = Kathleen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Feminists Who Changed America, 1963\u20131975|last = Love|first = Barbara|publisher = University of Illinois Press|year = 2006|isbn = 978-0252031892|location = Chicago|pages = [https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love/page/368 368]|url = https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love/page/368}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url = http://articles.latimes.com/1985-07-28/news/vw-5698_1_unpaid-work|title = Campaign Catches On: L.A. Pair Seek Wages for Women's Unpaid Work|last = Hendrix|first = Kathleen|date = 28 July  1985|work = Newspaper|access-date = 22 October 2015|via = Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nBoth San Francisco and Philadelphia were home to Wages Due Lesbians, an organization that was first created in Britain in 1975. Wages Due Lesbians called for wages for housework along with extra wages for lesbians for \"the additional physical and emotional housework of surviving in a hostile and prejudiced society, recognized as work and paid for so all women have the economic power to afford sexual choices.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Wages Due Lesbians also worked alongside The Lesbian Mothers' National Defense Fund, founded in 1974 and based in [[Seattle]], which aimed to help lesbian mothers who were a part of custody cases after coming out.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.outhistory.org/exhibits/show/lmndf/lmndf|title = The Lesbian Mothers National Defense Fund, the 1970s through 1990s|date = |accessdate = 6 November 2015|website = outhistory.org|publisher = Out History|last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = The A to Z of the Lesbian Liberation Movement: Still the Rage|last = Myers|first = JoAnne|publisher = Scarecrow Press|year = 2009|isbn = 978-0810863279|location = Plymouth|pages = xxxvi}}</ref>\n\nSan Francisco was also home to the U.S. PROStitutes Collective (US PROS). US PROS was created in 1982 to help decriminalize prostitution and also prevent men, women, and children from being forced into prostitution.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = US PROS Collective|url = http://uspros.net/|website = US PROS Collective|accessdate = 23 October 2015|language = en-US}}</ref> Likewise, Tulsa housed the No Bad Women, Just Bad Laws Coalitions. It was founded by Ruth Taylor Todasco in 1981 and also focused on the decriminalization of sex work.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Feminists Who Changed America, 1963\u20131965|last = Love|first = |publisher = |year = 2006|isbn = |location = |page = 463}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://hivandthelaw.com/sites/default/files/null/Overs_SexworkerRights.pdf|title = 'No Bad Women, Just Bad Laws': Three Decades of Sex Work Law Reform Advocacy|date = 2012|accessdate = 22 October 2015|website = HIV and the Law|publisher = Criminalize Hate Not HIV|last = Overs|first = Cheryl}}</ref>\n\n== Italy ==\nIn 1974, the Wages for Housework Campaign started in Italy. To celebrate, one of the founding members [[Mariarosa Dalla Costa]] gave a speech entitled \"A General Strike\" in [[Mestre]], Italy. In this speech she talks about how no strike before has ever been a general strike before, but instead, only a strike for male workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caringlabor.wordpress.com/2010/10/20/mariarosa-dalla-costa-a-general-strike/|title=A General Strike|last=Dalla Costa|first=Mariarosa|date=21 October 2010}}</ref>  \n\n== Social wage campaigns ==\nWages for Housework is part of more general [[social wage]] campaigns in the 1970s interested in [[late capitalism]].  These campaigns used analysis of [[Fordist]] compromises during the twentieth century to argue that [[family wages]] or social security payments had amounted to wages paid for housework in the advanced capitalist West.<ref name=Himmelweit>{{cite journal|last=Himmelweit|first=Susan F | last2 = Mohun | first2 = Simon | author-link1 = Susan Himmelweit | title = Domestic labour and capital |journal= Cambridge Journal of Economics |date=1977 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages= 15\u201331 |url =http://cje.oxfordjournals.org/content/1/1/15.full.pdf+html |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.cje.a035348 }}</ref><ref>Zo\u00eb Fairbairns, [http://www.newint.org/features/1988/03/05/wages/ \"Wages For Housework\"], ''New Internationalist'', issue 181, March 1988.</ref> A number of other autonomous organizations interested in compensation for domestic labor were formed in 1975: Black Women for Wages for Housework, Wages Due Lesbians, the [[English Collective of Prostitutes]] (ECP) and some years later WinVisible (women with visible and invisible disabilities).\n\n==Early influences==\nA number of early feminists focused women's economic independence along with the role of housewife in relation to women's oppression. In 1898 [[Charlotte Perkins Gilman]] published ''[[Women and Economics]].'' This book argued for paid housework 74 years before the International Wages for Housework Campaign was founded as well as arguing to expand the definition of women in the home.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Women and Economics: A Study of the Economic Relation Between Men and Women as a Factor in Social Evolution|last=Perkins Gilman|first=Charlotte|publisher=Small, Maynard & Company|year=1898|isbn=|location=United States|pages=}}</ref> She asserts that \"wives, as earners through domestic service, are entitled to the wages of cooks, housemaids, nursemaids, seamstresses, or housekeepers\" and that providing women economic independence is key to their liberation. [[Alva Myrdal]], a Swedish feminist, focused on state sponsored child care and housing, in order to ease the burden of parenting off mothers.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The Essential Feminist Reader|last=Freedman|first=Estelle|publisher=Modern Library|year=2007|isbn=9780812974607|location=|pages=}}</ref> In [[Simone de Beauvoir]]'s ''[[The Second Sex]],'' in which de Beauvoir asserts that women cannot find transcendence through unpaid house work.<ref name=\":4\" /> This idea is echoed in ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]'' by [[Betty Friedan]] when she discusses how women are unable to feel fulfilled in the home. ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]'' defined many second wave feminist goals, and the connection between the Wages for Housework Campaign and this work cannot be overlooked.<ref name=\":4\" />    \n\nIn 1965 Alison Ravetz published \"Modern Technology and an Ancient Occupation: Housework in Present-Day Society\"<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Modern Technology and an Ancient Occupation: Housework in Present-Day Society|journal = Technology and Culture|volume = 6|issue = 2|pages = 256\u2013260|last=Ravetz|first=Alison|jstor = 3101078|year = 1965|doi = 10.2307/3101078}}</ref> which critiques housework being a womanly duty post industrial revolution. The idea here is that since housework has become less labor intensive since then, it is even less fulfilling than ever before. This echos a similar argument made by [[Alva Myrdal]].\n\n==Recent history==\nThe demands of the Wages for Housework Campaign have been applied to many more recent debates in the gendered aspects of labor including, reproductive rights, sex work, and demands for women in leadership roles in business.<ref name=\"nplusonemag.com\" />\n\nSilvia Federici and several others from the early campaign have continued to publish books and articles related to the demands of Wages for Housework including: ''Revolution at Point Zero: Housework, Reproduction, and Feminist Struggle'' (2012), ''Wages for Housework: The New York Committee 1972\u20131977, History, Theory, and Documents'' (2017).\n\nThe Wages for Housework Campaign called for a [[Global Women's Strike|Global Women\u2019s Strike]] (GWS) on March 8, 2000, demanding among other things, \u201cPayment for all caring work \u2013 in wages, pensions, land and other resources.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=James|first=Selma|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/08/iceland-global-womens-strike-protest|title=Decades after Iceland\u2019s \u2018day off\u2019, our women\u2019s strike is stronger than ever {{!}} Selma James|date=2018-03-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Women from over 60 countries around the world participated in the protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/mar/07/gender|title=Stop the world and change it: the global women's strike|last=Staff|first=Guardian|date=2000-03-07|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since 2000 the GWS network has continued the call for a living wage for women and other caregivers, and they have led or joined campaigns focused on pay equity, violence against women, and the rights of sex workers, among other issues.\n\nIn 2019 the Global Women\u2019s Strike (GWS) network and Wages for Housework Campaign joined a coalition of organizations calling for a Green New Deal for Europe (GNDE).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gndforeurope.com/|title=Green New Deal for Europe|website=Green New Deal for Europe|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Wages for Housework Campaign co-founder, [[Selma James]] (with other GWS members), contributed to the GNDE platform report which includes a policy recommendation to \"fund a care income to compensate unpaid activities like care for people, the urban environment, and the natural world.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://report.gndforeurope.com/|title=A Blueprint for Europe's Just Transition|website=Green New Deal for Europe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The idea of a \u201ccare income\u201d expands the original demand for wages for housework to include all indispensable yet unpaid (or underpaid) work that involves caring for people and the planet, or caring for life. \n\nOn April 9, 2020, in response to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19 coronavirus]] pandemic and the climate emergency, the Global Women\u2019s Strike and Women of Colour GWS networks released an open letter to governments amplifying their call for a \u201ccare income.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalwomenstrike.net/press-statement-in-response-to-covid-19-and-the-climate-emergency-organizations-around-the-world-call-for-a-care-income-now/|title=PRESS STATEMENT: In response to Covid-19 and the climate emergency: organizations around the world call for a Care Income Now! \u2013 GLOBAL WOMEN'S STRIKE / WAGES FOR HOUSEWORK / SELMA JAMES|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nCritics of the Wages for Housework Campaign have argued that it could further reinforce or institutionalize specific gendered roles vis-\u00e0-vis housework, and care work more broadly. Instead they argue that feminists should focus on increasing women\u2019s opportunities in the paid workforce with pay equity, while promoting a more equal distribution of unpaid work in the household. Proponents of Wages for Housework do not oppose these ideas, however, they argue that entering the workforce does nothing to directly challenge the social role of women or result in a more equitable distribution of unpaid care work in the household. In fact, more often than not, women who have entered the paid workforce often face a \u201cdouble shift\u201d of work, the first paid work in the labor market and the second unpaid housework.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Federici, Silvia, author.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1129596584|title=Revolution at point zero : housework, reproduction, and feminist struggle|isbn=978-1-77113-494-1|oclc=1129596584}}</ref> According to one global estimate, women spend 4.5 hours of unpaid work per day, twice as many hours as men do on average.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gupta|first=Alisha Haridasani|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/23/us/unpaid-work-economy-davos.html|title=Women, Burdened With Unpaid Labor, Bear Brunt of Global Inequality|date=2020-01-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOther criticisms include the concern that providing wages for housework would commodify intimate human relationships of love and care and would subsume them into capitalist relations. However, proponents of wages for housework contest this \u201creductive view\u201d of their proposal. For instance, according to [[Silvia Federici]] the demand for wages for housework is not just about remuneration for unpaid work or women\u2019s financial empowerment and independence. Rather, it is a political perspective and a revolutionary strategy to make invisible work more visible, to demystify and disrupt the structural reliance of capitalism on the unpaid work of (mostly) women, and to subvert the supposed natural social role of \u201chousewife\u201d that capital has invented for women.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Federici, Silvia, author.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1129596584|title=Revolution at point zero : housework, reproduction, and feminist struggle|isbn=978-1-77113-494-1|oclc=1129596584}}</ref>\n\nWhat\u2019s more, the payment of wages for housework would mean that capital would have to pay for the immense amount of unpaid care work (undertaken largely by women) that currently reproduces the labor force. According to a report by Oxfam and the Institute for Women\u2019s Policy Research, the monetary value of unpaid care work is estimated at nearly $11 trillion a year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wezerek|first=Gus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/04/opinion/women-unpaid-labor.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Women\u2019s Unpaid Labor is Worth $10,900,000,000,000|date=2020-03-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|last2=Ghodsee|first2=Kristen R.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfamamerica.org/explore/research-publications/time-care/|title=Time to Care|website=www.oxfamamerica.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> This amounts to an enormous subsidy to the capitalist economy, and paying for it would likely render the current system uneconomic, subverting the social relations in the process. \n\nMonetary estimates of this kind are used to demonstrate the scale of unpaid work in relation to more visible waged work. However, proponents of wages for housework (and similar  more recent ideas, e.g. caregivers allowance<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fraser|first=Nancy|date=1994|title=After the Family Wage: Gender Equity and the Welfare State|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/192041|journal=Political Theory|volume=22|issue=4|pages=591\u2013618|issn=0090-5917}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bostonreview.net/archives/BR19.1/fraser.html|title=Reinventing the Welfare State|last=Fraser|first=Nancy|date=February\u2013March 1994|website=bostonreview.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> or care income<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://report.gndforeurope.com/|title=A Blueprint for Europe's Just Transition|website=Green New Deal for Europe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalwomenstrike.net/open-letter-to-governments-a-care-income-now/|title=Open letter to governments \u2013 a Care Income Now! \u2013 GLOBAL WOMEN'S STRIKE / WAGES FOR HOUSEWORK / SELMA JAMES|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>) have rarely called for the marketization and commodification of unpaid care work. Instead they have promoted public funding for these schemes as part of a larger project of recognizing and revaluing the indispensable role of unpaid care work for society and the economy. Some feminist scholars have also called for the creation of new commons-based systems of care and basic provisioning that operate outside of the market and state, and for the defense of existing commons, especially in communities of the [[Global South]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wealthofthecommons.org/essay/feminism-and-politics-commons|title=Feminism and the Politics of the Commons {{!}} The Wealth of the Commons|website=wealthofthecommons.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* [[Louise Toupin]]. ''Le salaire au travail m\u00e9nager. Chronique d'une lutte f\u00e9ministe internationale (1972\u20131977)'' \u00c9ditions du Remue-M\u00e9nage, 2014.\n* Silvia Federici. ''Revolution at Point Zero: Housework, Reproduction, and Feminist Struggle.'' PM Press, 2012. \n*  Silvia Federici. ''[https://monoskop.org/images/2/23/Federici_Silvia_Wages_Against_Housework_1975.pdf Wages Against Housework]''. Published jointly by the Power of Women Collective and Falling Wall Press, 1975. Link goes to full text of the book.\n* Cox, Nicole, and Silvia Federici. ''[http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce.htm Counter-planning from the kitchen: wages for housework : a perspective on capital and the Left.''] New York: New York Wages for Housework Committee. 1976.\n* Dalla Costa, Mariarosa, and Selma James. ''The Power of Women and the Subversion of the Community.'' Bristol: Falling Wall Press Ltd. 1975.\n* James, Selma, Nina Lopez, and Marcus Rediker. 2012. ''Sex, Race and Class \u2013 The Perspective of Winning a Selection of Writings 1952\u20132011.'' Chicago: PM Press. http://public.eblib.com/EBLPublic/PublicView.do?ptiID=867353.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Microwork]]\n* [[Post-Fordism]]\n* [[Knowledge economy]]\n* [[Knowledge market]]\n*[[Marxist feminism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nbjournal.org/2007/07/selma-james-and-the-wages-for-housework-campaign/ Selma James and the Wages for Housework Campaign - article by Shemon Salam in New Beginnings, a journal of independent labour]\n* [http://bcrw.barnard.edu/archive/workforce.htm \"Women in the Workforce\" collections. Barnard Archive.]\n* [http://globalwomenstrike.net/ Global Women's Strike/ Wages For Housework/ Selma James website]\n*[https://www.gndforeurope.com/campaign Green New Deal for Europe campaign website] \n\n[[Category:Feminism]]\n[[Category:Wages and salaries]]\n[[Category:Trade unions]]\n[[Category:Autonomism]]\n", "name_user": "Brian.p.emerson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversies:Clarified some of the language and deleted unnecessary citations.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wages_for_housework"}
{"title_page": "Punggol East Single Member Constituency", "text_new": "{{Infobox constituency\n|type=Single Member\n|name=Punggol East\n|year=2011\n|parl_name=[[Parliament of Singapore]]\n|member=[[Charles Chong]]\n|image=[[File:Punggol East SMC locator map.svg|240px]]\n|region=Northeastern [[Singapore]]\n|electorate=35,436\n|local_council_label=Town Council\n|local_council=Pasir Ris-Punggol\n|abolished=2020}}\n:''Not to be confused with the pre-independence era ward in [[Punggol]] and [[Hougang]] areas called the Punggol Member Constituency which was formed prior to [[1959 Singaporean general election|1959 general elections]] by carving out a portion of the then-defunct [[Punggol-Tampines SMC]], which lasted until prior to [[1991 Singaporean general election|1991 general elections]] when that ward was absorbed into the then defunct [[Cheng San GRC]].''\n\n'''Punggol East Single Member Constituency''' ({{zh|\u699c\u9e45\u4e1c\u5355\u9009\u533a}}; {{lang-ms|Kawasan Undi Perseorangan Punggol East}}; {{lang-ta|\u0baa\u0bca\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b88\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bca\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbf}}) was a [[Single Member Constituency]] located in the [[North-East Region, Singapore|north-eastern]] area of [[Singapore]]. Despite its name, the ward does not cover the town of [[Punggol]] but rather its boundaries span the neighbourhood of Rivervale, the eastern area of [[Sengkang]]. This ward has been carved out during the [[2011 Singaporean general election|2011's General Election]] and was formerly a ward from the [[Pasir Ris-Punggol Group Representation Constituency|Pasir Ris-Punggol GRC]].\n\nOn 12 December 2012, then MP for Punggol East SMC, [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]] resigned after an extramarital affair was revealed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1242365/1/.html | title=Speaker of Parliament Michael Palmer resigns over \"grave mistake\" | publisher=Channel NewsAsia | date=December 12, 2012 | accessdate=January 28, 2013}}</ref> A by-election was held on 26 January 2013, and [[Lee Li Lian]] of the [[Workers' Party of Singapore|Workers' Party]] was elected as MP.<ref name=\"LLL\">{{cite web | url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1250425/1/.html | title=WP's Lee wins Punggol East by-election | publisher=Channel NewsAsia |date=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2015 Singaporean general election|2015 general elections]], PAP's [[Charles Chong]] won in Punggol East SMC, replacing [[Lee Li Lian]] as MP for the constituency.<ref name=\"ST GE2015\">{{cite news|last1=Sim|first1=Royston|title=GE2015: PAP's Charles Chong wins Punggol East SMC with 51.76 per cent of votes|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/politics/ge2015-pap-slightly-ahead-in-punggol-east-smc-sample-count-with-51-per-cent|accessdate=22 September 2015|work=The Straits Times|agency=SPH|date=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of the Electoral Boundaries Review committee report for the [[2020 Singaporean general election|2020 general elections]], Punggol East SMC will be absorbed into a brand new 4-member [[Sengkang Group Representation Constituency|Sengkang GRC]], effectively dissolving the single constituency. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe ward was previously belong to the [[Pasir Ris-Punggol Group Representation Constituency]] when the division was first created in 2006. In 2011, the ward was carved out as a SMC, and it was the sole constituency to feature a three-cornered contest for the election (and also the first three-cornered contest since 2001, where it contested [[Bukit Timah SMC]]). The election was won by then-MP, Michael Palmer, who was the incumbent of the ward with 54.54% of the votes, beating WP's newcomer Lee Li Lian and SDA's secretary-general Desmond Lim, who garnered 41.01% and 4.45% of the votes, respectively. Lim was the only candidate to have garnered less than the 12.5% vote threshold, and thus lost the deposit.\n\nFollowing Palmer's resignation on December, the ward was temporary substituted by Minister of State [[Teo Ser Luck]], who was the MP of the neighbouring Pasir Ris-Pungggol GRC. On 10 January 2013, [[People's Action Party|PAP]] unveiled their candidate for the by-election: Dr [[Koh Poh Koon]], a 40-year-old colorectal surgeon from [[Mount Elizabeth Medical Centre]], who had joined the party only three weeks prior. Both WP's Lee and SDA's Lim had returned to contest the by-election. The election also featured a fourth candidate, the Secretary-general of [[Reform Party (Singapore)|Reform Party]], [[Kenneth Jeyaretnam]], who he previously contested [[West Coast Group Representation Constituency]] in the 2011 election.\n\nThere were two rounds of rallies in this by-election, [[Workers' Party of Singapore|Workers' Party]]'s rally drew the most audiences amounting ranging 5,000 to 12,000 audiences, while [[Singapore Democratic Alliance]] using the social media and technology to draw audiences via a series of videos posted to [[YouTube]].\n\nDuring the vote counting, SDA's Desmond Lim officially conceded defeat.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Channel NewsAsia|title=SDA's Lim concedes defeat|date=26 January 2013|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1250423/1/.html}}</ref> Jeyaretnam and Lim both lost their election deposit in this by-election, with Lim as the only the second candidate to date whom as lost his deposit twice, after Harbans Singh of the United People's Front.<ref>[http://singapore-elections.com/candidates/h-i.html#HS Candidates name list (H-I): Harbans Singh]</ref> At 0.57%, Lim also set a record for the lowest percentage garnered in an election since post-independence Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130127-398101.html|title=SDA scores worst result in post-independence history|website=www.asiaone.com}}</ref>\n\nWP's Lee won the by-election with 16,038 votes, or 54.52% (Including overseas votes, the percentage of valid votes cast were 54.50%, or 16,045 votes), marking the second by-election where an opposition had won a parliament seat from the ruling party, after [[1981 Anson by-election|1981]]. She was sworn in at the Parliament on 4 February 2013, and held her Meet-The-People session on the same day.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1252219/1/.html | title=WP's Lee Li Lian holds first Meet-the-People session | publisher=Channel NewsAsia | date=February 4, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis ward has been absorbed into a new Sengkang GRC for the [[2020 Singaporean general election|2020 general election]], after the Electoral Boundaries Review Committee (EBRC) released its report on 13 March 2020, and renamed '''Sengkang East'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n{| class=wikitable\n|- valign=bottom\n! Member of Parliament\n! colspan=\"2\" | Party\n! Dates\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]]\n| bgcolor={{People's Action Party/meta/color}} | || [[People's Action Party|PAP]]\n| 2011\u20132013\n| Resigned after an extramarital affair came to light, precipitating the [[2013 Singaporean by-election|Punggol-East by-election]]\n|-\n| [[Lee Li Lian]]\n| bgcolor=#0087DC | || [[The Workers' Party (Singapore)|WP]]\n| 2013\u20132015\n|\n|-\n|Charles Chong\n| bgcolor={{People's Action Party/meta/color}} | || [[People's Action Party|PAP]]\n|2015\u2013\n|Incumbent\n|}\n\n==Candidates and results==\n\n===Elections in 2010s===\n{{Election box begin | title=[[2015 Singaporean general election|General Election 2015]]: Punggol East}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = People's Action Party\n |candidate = [[Charles Chong]]\n |votes = 16,957\n |percentage = 51.76\n |change = +8.03\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Workers' Party of Singapore\n |candidate = [[Lee Li Lian]]\n |votes = 15,801\n |percentage = 48.24\n |change = -6.26\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n|votes= 1,156\n|percentage= 3.52\n|change= \n}}\n{{Election box rejected\n|votes= 379\n|percentage= 1.14\n|change= -0.26\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n|votes= 33,137\n|percentage= 96.14\n|change= +1.83\n}}\n{{Election box Registered electors\n|reg. electors= 34,466\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = People's Action Party\n |loser = Workers' Party of Singapore\n |swing = +6.83\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[2013 Singaporean by-election|By-Election 2013]]: Punggol East}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Workers' Party of Singapore\n |candidate = [[Lee Li Lian]]\n |votes = 16,045\n |percentage = 54.50\n |change = +13.49\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = People's Action Party\n |candidate = [[Koh Poh Koon]]\n |votes = 12,875\n |percentage = 43.73\n |change = -10.81\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Reform Party (Singapore)\n |candidate = [[Kenneth Jeyaretnam]] <small>'''(Loses deposit)'''</small>\n |votes = 353\n |percentage = 1.20\n |change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Singapore Democratic Alliance\n |candidate = Desmond Lim Bak Chuan <small>'''(Loses deposit)'''</small>\n |votes = 168\n |percentage = 0.57\n |change = -3.88\n}}\n{{Election box margin of victory\n|votes= 3,170\n|percentage= 10.77\n|change= -2.76\n}}\n{{Election box rejected\n|votes= 418\n|percentage= 1.40\n|change= -0.3\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n|votes= 29,859\n|percentage= 94.31\n|change= -0.99\n}}\n{{Election box Registered electors\n|reg. electors= 31,659\n|percentage= 100\n|change= -4.9%\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Workers' Party of Singapore\n |loser = People's Action Party\n |swing = +12.15\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[2011 Singaporean general election|General Election 2011]]: Punggol East}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = People's Action Party\n |candidate = [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]]\n |votes = 16,994\n |percentage = 54.54\n |change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Workers' Party of Singapore\n |candidate = [[Lee Li Lian]]\n |votes = 12,777\n |percentage = 41.01\n |change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Singapore Democratic Alliance\n |candidate = Desmond Lim Bak Chuan <small>'''(Loses deposit)'''</small>\n |votes = 1,387\n |percentage = 4.45\n |change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = 31,709\n |percentage = 95.3\n |change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box new seat win |\n |winner = People's Action Party}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pasir Ris-Punggol GRC]]\n* [[Punggol SMC]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://www.elections.gov.sg/elections_results2011.html#P Result of 2011 General Election]\n* [http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1242365/1/.html#B Resignation of Michael Palmer, MP, Punggol East SMC]\n\n{{Constituencies of Singapore}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Singapore}}\n\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 disestablishments in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Singaporean electoral divisions]]\n[[Category:Sengkang]]\n[[Category:Constituencies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Constituencies disestablished in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox constituency\n|type=Single Member\n|name=Punggol East\n|year=2011\n|parl_name=[[Parliament of Singapore]]\n|member=[[Charles Chong]]\n|image=[[File:Punggol East SMC locator map.svg|240px]]\n|region=Northeastern [[Singapore]]\n|electorate=35,436\n|local_council_label=Town Council\n|local_council=Pasir Ris-Punggol\n|abolished=2020}}\n:''Not to be confused with the pre-independence era ward in [[Punggol]] and [[Hougang]] areas called the Punggol Member Constituency which was formed prior to [[1959 Singaporean general election|1959 general elections]] by carving out a portion of the then-defunct [[Punggol-Tampines SMC]], which lasted until prior to [[1991 Singaporean general election|1991 general elections]] when that ward was absorbed into the then defunct [[Cheng San GRC]].''\n\n'''Punggol East Single Member Constituency''' ({{zh|\u699c\u9e45\u4e1c\u5355\u9009\u533a}}; {{lang-ms|Kawasan Undi Perseorangan Punggol East}}; {{lang-ta|\u0baa\u0bca\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b88\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bca\u0b95\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbf}}) was a [[Single Member Constituency]] located in the [[North-East Region, Singapore|north-eastern]] area of [[Singapore]]. Despite its name, the ward does not cover the town of [[Punggol]] but rather its boundaries span the neighbourhood of Rivervale, the eastern area of [[Sengkang]]. This ward has been carved out during the [[2011 Singaporean general election|2011's General Election]] and was formerly a ward from the [[Pasir Ris-Punggol Group Representation Constituency|Pasir Ris-Punggol GRC]].\n\nOn 12 December 2012, then MP for Punggol East SMC, [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]] resigned after an extramarital affair was revealed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1242365/1/.html | title=Speaker of Parliament Michael Palmer resigns over \"grave mistake\" | publisher=Channel NewsAsia | date=December 12, 2012 | accessdate=January 28, 2013}}</ref> A by-election was held on 26 January 2013, and [[Lee Li Lian]] of the [[Workers' Party of Singapore|Workers' Party]] was elected as MP.<ref name=\"LLL\">{{cite web | url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1250425/1/.html | title=WP's Lee wins Punggol East by-election | publisher=Channel NewsAsia |date=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2015 Singaporean general election|2015 general elections]], PAP's [[Charles Chong]] won in Punggol East SMC, replacing [[Lee Li Lian]] as MP for the constituency.<ref name=\"ST GE2015\">{{cite news|last1=Sim|first1=Royston|title=GE2015: PAP's Charles Chong wins Punggol East SMC with 51.76 per cent of votes|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/politics/ge2015-pap-slightly-ahead-in-punggol-east-smc-sample-count-with-51-per-cent|accessdate=22 September 2015|work=The Straits Times|agency=SPH|date=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of the Electoral Boundaries Review committee report for the [[2020 Singaporean general election|2020 general elections]], Punggol East SMC will be absorbed into a brand new 4-member [[Sengkang Group Representation Constituency|Sengkang GRC]], effectively dissolving the single constituency. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe ward was previously belong to the [[Pasir Ris-Punggol Group Representation Constituency]] when the division was first created in 2006. In 2011, the ward was carved out as a SMC, and it was the sole constituency to feature a three-cornered contest for the election (and also the first three-cornered contest since 2001, where it contested [[Bukit Timah SMC]]). The election was won by then-MP, Michael Palmer, who was the incumbent of the ward with 54.54% of the votes, beating WP's newcomer Lee Li Lian and SDA's secretary-general Desmond Lim, who garnered 41.01% and 4.45% of the votes, respectively. Lim was the only candidate to have garnered less than the 12.5% vote threshold, and thus lost the deposit.\n\nFollowing Palmer's resignation on December, the ward was temporary substituted by Minister of State [[Teo Ser Luck]], who was the MP of the neighbouring Pasir Ris-Pungggol GRC. On 10 January 2013, [[People's Action Party|PAP]] unveiled their candidate for the by-election: Dr [[Koh Poh Koon]], a 40-year-old colorectal surgeon from [[Mount Elizabeth Medical Centre]], who had joined the party only three weeks prior. Both WP's Lee and SDA's Lim had returned to contest the by-election. The election also featured a fourth candidate, the Secretary-general of [[Reform Party (Singapore)|Reform Party]], [[Kenneth Jeyaretnam]], who he previously contested [[West Coast Group Representation Constituency]] in the 2011 election.\n\nThere were two rounds of rallies in this by-election, [[Workers' Party of Singapore|Workers' Party]]'s rally drew the most audiences amounting ranging 5,000 to 12,000 audiences, while [[Singapore Democratic Alliance]] using the social media and technology to draw audiences via a series of videos posted to [[YouTube]].\n\nDuring the vote counting, SDA's Desmond Lim officially conceded defeat.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Channel NewsAsia|title=SDA's Lim concedes defeat|date=26 January 2013|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1250423/1/.html}}</ref> Jeyaretnam and Lim both lost their election deposit in this by-election, with Lim as the only the second candidate to date whom as lost his deposit twice, after Harbans Singh of the United People's Front.<ref>[http://singapore-elections.com/candidates/h-i.html#HS Candidates name list (H-I): Harbans Singh]</ref> At 0.57%, Lim also set a record for the lowest percentage garnered in an election since post-independence Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130127-398101.html|title=SDA scores worst result in post-independence history|website=www.asiaone.com}}</ref>\n\nWP's Lee won the by-election with 16,038 votes, or 54.52% (Including overseas votes, the percentage of valid votes cast were 54.50%, or 16,045 votes), marking the second by-election where an opposition had won a parliament seat from the ruling party, after [[1981 Anson by-election|1981]]. She was sworn in at the Parliament on 4 February 2013, and held her Meet-The-People session on the same day.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1252219/1/.html | title=WP's Lee Li Lian holds first Meet-the-People session | publisher=Channel NewsAsia | date=February 4, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis ward has been absorbed into a new Sengkang GRC for the [[2020 Singaporean general election|2020 general election]], after the Electoral Boundaries Review Committee (EBRC) released its report on 13 March 2020, and renamed '''Sengkang East'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n{| class=wikitable\n|- valign=bottom\n! Member of Parliament\n! colspan=\"2\" | Party\n! Dates\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]]\n| bgcolor={{People's Action Party/meta/color}} | || [[People's Action Party|PAP]]\n| 2011\u20132013\n| Resigned after an extramarital affair came to light, precipitating the [[2013 Singaporean by-election|Punggol-East by-election]]\n|-\n| [[Lee Li Lian]]\n| bgcolor=#0087DC | || [[The Workers' Party (Singapore)|WP]]\n| 2013\u20132015\n|\n|-\n|Charles Chong\n| bgcolor={{People's Action Party/meta/color}} | || [[People's Action Party|PAP]]\n|2015\u2013\n|Incumbent\n|}\n\n==Candidates and results==\n\n===Elections in 2010s===\n{{Election box begin | titl